Here's What You Need to Know Right Now

The stock is currently trading at $146.71 (as of December 2025), and it's currently in a bearish trend, trading below both its 50-day and 200-day moving averages.

Analysts appear optimistic, with a 1-year price target of $169.05 (a potential +14.5% upside). However, there's significant volatility here (14.3% annualized), suggesting the potential for wide price swings.

The Procter & Gamble Company's fundamental story is nuanced. On one hand, the company benefits from strong profitability with a 1974.00% profit margin. On the other, it faces challenges with intense competition in its sector.

Company Description

A brief overview of the company's business activities. The Procter & Gamble Company provides branded consumer packaged goods worldwide. It operates through Beauty; Grooming; Health Care; Fabric & Home Care; and Baby, Feminine & Family Care segments.

The company offers conditioners, shampoos, styling aids, and treatments under the Head & Shoulders, Herbal Essences, Pantene, and Rejoice brands; antiperspirants, deodorants, and personal cleansing products under the Native, Old Spice, Safeguard, and Secret brands;

and facial moisturizers, cleaners, and treatments under the Olay and SK-II brands. It also provides blades, razors, shave products, appliances, and other grooming products under the Braun, Gillette, and Venus brands. In addition, the company offers toothbrushes, toothpastes, and other oral care products under the Crest and Oral-B brands;

and gastrointestinal, pain relief, rapid diagnostics, respiratory, vitamins/minerals/supplements, and other personal health care products under the Metamucil, Neurobion, Pepto-Bismol, and Vicks brands. Further, it provides fabric enhancers, and laundry additives and detergents under the Ariel, Downy, Gain, and Tide brands;

and air and dish care, P&G professional, and surface care under the Cascade, Dawn, Fairy, Febreze, Mr. Clean, and Swiffer brands. Additionally, the company offers baby wipes, and taped diapers and pants under the Luvs and Pampers brands;

adult incontinence and menstrual care products under the Always, Always Discreet, and Tampax brands;

and paper towels, tissues, and toilet papers under the Bounty, Charmin, and Puffs brands. It sells its products through mass merchandisers, social and e-commerce channels, grocery and specialty beauty stores, membership club stores, drug and department stores, distributors, wholesalers, airport duty-free and high-frequency stores, pharmacies, electronics stores, and professional channels, as well as directly to consumers.

The Procter & Gamble Company was founded in 1837 and is headquartered in Cincinnati, Ohio.

Essentially, you're paying for quality - but quality doesn't come cheap.

Profitability and Growth

An analysis of the key metrics in PG's margin performance shows the company has solid control over its costs and prices. The company is successful in controlling its production costs, as shown by the gross margin of 51.28%, and it also profits well from its core operations, reflected in the 27.58% operating margin. A 29.11% EBITDA margin indicates PG is capable of generating strong cash flow from its operations before accounting for financing and tax strategies. All things considered, PG can hold onto around $19.740 in net profit for every $1 of its revenue over the last twelve months. While the business's revenue is increasing at an aggressive rate (3.00%), investors should monitor if this pace can be sustained without eroding profit margins.

PG's 24.72 B in EBITDA and 43.55 B in gross profit indicate its raw earning power, while the 16.47 B in net income reveals how effectively it converts that power into bottom-line results. The company appears to be balancing its pursuit of growth with the need to maintain profitability. Despite healthy gross margins, there is a significant difference between the company's gross and net margins (51.28% vs. 19.74%). This is likely due to high operating expenses, interest costs, or taxes, which are key areas for investors to watch. In the future, maintaining steady or improving margins will be critical. PG needs to defend its pricing power and control operating costs, as this will help sustain profitability, especially if revenue growth moderates.

Dividends and Shareholder Returns

Dividend Summary & Investor Implications

The company currently offers a $4.23 annual dividend per share, translating to a dividend yield of 2.88%‚Äîmeaning for every $100 invested, shareholders receive $4.23 in dividends annually. This yield is above its 5-year average of 2.43%, making it more attractive to income investors today compared to its recent history.

Key Observations & Analysis:

  • The payout ratio of 60.24% is healthy, indicating the company uses only ~60% of its earnings to fund dividends. This leaves ample room for future increases or reinvestment in growth.
  • The very low trailing yield of 3.00% hints at a recent dividend initiation or a special, non-recurring payout, warranting further checks for consistency.
  • Investors must own the stock before the upcoming ex-dividend date of 2025-10-24 to receive the next dividend.
  • The last stock split (2:1 in 2004) is outdated and likely irrelevant to the current valuation.

Investor Takeaway:

  • Income Investors: The dividend appears sustainable, but investors should monitor earnings and cash flow to ensure the payout remains well-supported.
  • Growth Investors: The company maintains a balance between shareholder returns and reinvestment, appealing to a 'growth and income' strategy.
  • Watch For: Announcements of dividend hikes (which could bring the yield closer to its historical average) or significant stock price changes that would alter the yield.
